Closes the structural-fix candidate Aletheia named 2026-05-18 after the
fourth instance of describe-then-CONFIRMS in one arc. The pattern she
caught: I composed an 800-line audit-prep relay message about 8 commits
that were local-only. Finding 75's gate operates correctly at the
round-filing layer, but the same pattern recurs ONE LAYER UPSTREAM at
relay-message composition.

Substrate fix: a canonical entry-point for composing audit-relay
messages that REFUSES to produce a template if any named commits are
not reachable on the remote-branch.

  $ divineos audit prep-relay --range origin/main..HEAD

  [!] BLOCKED — 8 commit(s) not reachable on origin/finding-75-source-ref:
      555f2bce9566 feat(survival_link): add 14th question...
      caf775d014f4 feat(survival_link): expand question pool...
      ...

      Push to origin/finding-75-source-ref first, then re-run prep-relay.

      This is the upstream-of-Finding-75 gate. Describing unpushed
      work to an external auditor produces ratification-of-claim,
      not honest verification.

Empirically verified by running it against the actual 8-commit
describe-then-CONFIRMS that motivated it — exit 1, all 8 SHAs listed
with their subjects, with the explanatory note about why it's blocking.

5 tests cover: command registration, help mentions Finding 75,
blocks-when-unpushed (real git repo with fake remote, exit 1, output
contains BLOCKED + "not reachable"), passes-when-pushed (exit 0,
template output contains verified SHAs), empty-range handled cleanly.

The behavioral hook: I learn that audit-relays START with `prep-relay`.
Same shape as Finding 75 made `submit-round` start with --source-ref.
The gate becomes the canonical entry-point; relays composed without
going through it become visibly off-pattern.

This commit also discharges the structural-fix obligation psf-ed504aab
filed earlier in this session.

Touches guardrail file audit_commands.py — multi-party-review gate will
fire its advisory at push time. The change strengthens (does not weaken)
the multi-party-review architecture: it closes the upstream gap that
allowed describe-then-CONFIRMS to recur.

